                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <p>But it's not just AI-specific roles. <strong>Cybersecurity experts, cloud computing specialists, and datacenter technicians</strong> remain in strong demand as companies build the infrastructure to support AI workloads.</p>

        <div class="highlight-box">
            <h3>üí° Key Insight</h3>
            <p><strong>AI fluency is no longer optional.</strong> Whether you're a software developer, marketing professional, financial analyst, or even in HR‚Äîunderstanding how to work with AI tools is becoming a baseline expectation across industries. Skills like using LLMs and understanding prompt engineering are now essential.</p>
        </div>

        <h2>Threat or Opportunity?</h2>
        <p>Yes, AI is automating certain tasks. Entry-level work that once served as the gateway to careers‚Äîdata entry, basic analysis, routine customer service‚Äîis increasingly being handled by AI systems. This has understandably created anxiety among fresh graduates and early-career professionals.</p>

        <p><strong>But disruption always creates opportunity.</strong> The same technology that automates routine tasks creates demand for people who can:</p>

        <ul class="tips-list">
            <li>
                <span class="tip-icon">ü§ù</span>
                <div class="tip-content">
                    <strong>Work alongside AI</strong>
                    <p>Collaborate with AI systems to enhance productivity and output quality</p>
                </div>
            </li>
            <li>
                <span class="tip-icon">‚öôÔ∏è</span>
